{"parentUuid":"bea59b8c-8fbc-40cb-9454-71dbed1a0f25","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b83cd85c-215e-4dfb-b12b-82fa27341e0f","agentId":"a694ec9ee8d30ccac","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015N6Jqzzym2kzuWGiDoTS7q","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"arstechnica.com AlphaEvolve Gemini algorithm discovery automatic evaluation\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve: How AI-Driven Algorithm Discovery Is Rewriting Computing | by Greg Robison | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://gregrobison.medium.com/alphaevolve-how-ai-driven-algorithm-discovery-is-rewriting-computing-4f27c88d8b27\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve: A Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms — Google DeepMind\",\"url\":\"https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\"},{\"title\":\"Google DeepMind’s AlphaEvolve: A Breakthrough AI Coding Agent | SSOJet - Enterprise SSO & Identity Solutions\",\"url\":\"https://ssojet.com/blog/google-deepminds-alphaevolve-a-breakthrough-ai-coding-agent\"},{\"title\":\"Meet AlphaEvolve, the Google AI that writes its own code—and just saved millions in computing costs | VentureBeat\",\"url\":\"https://venturebeat.com/ai/meet-alphaevolve-the-google-ai-that-writes-its-own-code-and-just-saved-millions-in-computing-costs\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\",\"url\":\"https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve on Google Cloud | Google Cloud Blog\",\"url\":\"https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/ai-machine-learning/alphaevolve-on-google-cloud/\"},{\"title\":\"Building Production-Ready Probes For Gemini\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.11516\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve: Gemini-powered coding agent scaling impact across fields — Google DeepMind\",\"url\":\"https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-impact/\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, I found information about AlphaEvolve and its use of Gemini models with automatic evaluation, though I didn't find a specific Ars Technica article with that exact focus. Here's what the search revealed:\n\nAlphaEvolve is an evolutionary coding agent powered by large language models for general-purpose algorithm discovery and optimization that pairs the creative problem-solving capabilities of Gemini models with automated evaluators that verify answers, and uses an evolutionary framework to improve upon the most promising ideas.\n\nAlphaEvolve verifies, runs and scores the proposed programs using automated evaluation metrics. The system uses Gemini models (Flash for speed, Pro for depth) to process the context and generate mutated, optimized versions of the code that are added to the \"population space.\"\n\nBy discovering smarter approaches to matrix multiplication operations, AlphaEvolve achieved a 23% speedup for this critical kernel in Gemini's architecture, and its optimization of low-level GPU instructions delivered a huge 32.5% speedup for the FlashAttention kernel implementation in Transformer-based AI models.\n\nThe search results included articles from Google DeepMind's official blog, Medium, VentureBeat, and Google Cloud Blog, but I did not find a specific Ars Technica article matching your exact search query.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"aa2c05b6-11ca-4e8a-b3e2-f0c667b1d415","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:57.735Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"arstechnica.com AlphaEvolve Gemini algorithm discovery automatic evaluation","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01LbKYkNJGdHmWkCCRETAU6J","content":[{"title":"AlphaEvolve: How AI-Driven Algorithm Discovery Is Rewriting Computing | by Greg Robison | Medium","url":"https://gregrobison.medium.com/alphaevolve-how-ai-driven-algorithm-discovery-is-rewriting-computing-4f27c88d8b27"},{"title":"AlphaEvolve: A Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms — Google DeepMind","url":"https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/"},{"title":"Google DeepMind’s AlphaEvolve: A Breakthrough AI Coding Agent | SSOJet - Enterprise SSO & Identity Solutions","url":"https://ssojet.com/blog/google-deepminds-alphaevolve-a-breakthrough-ai-coding-agent"},{"title":"Meet AlphaEvolve, the Google AI that writes its own code—and just saved millions in computing costs | VentureBeat","url":"https://venturebeat.com/ai/meet-alphaevolve-the-google-ai-that-writes-its-own-code-and-just-saved-millions-in-computing-costs"},{"title":"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery","url":"https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf"},{"title":"AlphaEvolve on Google Cloud | Google Cloud Blog","url":"https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/ai-machine-learning/alphaevolve-on-google-cloud/"},{"title":"Building Production-Ready Probes For Gemini","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.11516"},{"title":"AlphaEvolve: Gemini-powered coding agent scaling impact across fields — Google DeepMind","url":"https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-impact/"}]},"Based on the search results, I found information about AlphaEvolve and its use of Gemini models with automatic evaluation, though I didn't find a specific Ars Technica article with that exact focus. Here's what the search revealed:\n\nAlphaEvolve is an evolutionary coding agent powered by large language models for general-purpose algorithm discovery and optimization that pairs the creative problem-solving capabilities of Gemini models with automated evaluators that verify answers, and uses an evolutionary framework to improve upon the most promising ideas.\n\nAlphaEvolve verifies, runs and scores the proposed programs using automated evaluation metrics. The system uses Gemini models (Flash for speed, Pro for depth) to process the context and generate mutated, optimized versions of the code that are added to the \"population space.\"\n\nBy discovering smarter approaches to matrix multiplication operations, AlphaEvolve achieved a 23% speedup for this critical kernel in Gemini's architecture, and its optimization of low-level GPU instructions delivered a huge 32.5% speedup for the FlashAttention kernel implementation in Transformer-based AI models.\n\nThe search results included articles from Google DeepMind's official blog, Medium, VentureBeat, and Google Cloud Blog, but I did not find a specific Ars Technica article matching your exact search query."],"durationSeconds":10.241107166999951,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"bea59b8c-8fbc-40cb-9454-71dbed1a0f25","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"aa2c05b6-11ca-4e8a-b3e2-f0c667b1d415","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a694ec9ee8d30ccac","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_012pBJynpLqzPGKXbT5Gvg7R","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have strong primary-source material plus VentureBeat and TechCrunch for secondary framing. I have everything needed. Here are the findings.\n\n---\n\n# AlphaEvolve (Google DeepMind, 2025): The Role of the Verifier / Evaluation Function\n\nAll claims below are falsifiable and tied to exact source URLs. The two primary sources are the DeepMind white paper PDF and the DeepMind blog post.\n\n**Primary sources:**\n- White paper PDF: `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf` (title: *\"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\"*)\n- Blog post: `https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n\n---\n\n## A. The verifier IS the core mechanism (every candidate is machine-scored)\n\n**Claim 1 — AlphaEvolve only tackles problems with machine-gradable solutions; the user must supply an automated assessor.**\n> \"Since AlphaEvolve tackles problems with machine-gradeable solutions, the user must provide a mechanism for automatically assessing generated solutions.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, §2.1 Task specification — `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf`\n\nNote the exact DeepMind spelling is **\"machine-gradeable\"** (with the extra \"e\").\n\n**Claim 2 — The verifier is a function h mapping a solution to a set of scalar metrics, which are maximized.**\n> \"This mechanism takes the form of a function ℎ mapping a solution to a set of scalar evaluation metrics. By convention, these metrics are maximized. In our current setup, ℎ is typically implemented as a Python function, called evaluate, with a fixed input/output signature, returning a dictionary of scalars.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, §2.1 — same URL.\n\n**Claim 3 — Evaluation = simply executing the user-provided function h on each candidate.**\n> \"each new solution proposed by the LLMs is automatically evaluated. In principle, this process amounts to simply executing the user-provided evaluation function ℎ on the generated solution.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, §2.4 Evaluation — same URL.\n\n**Claim 4 — The evolutionary loop is driven entirely by the score from automated metrics.**\n> The orchestrator is \"an evolutionary algorithm that gradually develops programs that improve the score on the automated evaluation metrics associated with the task.\"\nSource: White paper PDF (line ~123) — same URL.\n\n**Claim 5 — Blog post phrasing: AlphaEvolve \"verifies, runs and scores\" via automated metrics.**\n> \"AlphaEvolve verifies, runs and scores the proposed programs using automated evaluation metrics. These metrics provide an objective, quantifiable assessment of each solution's accuracy and quality.\"\nSource: DeepMind blog post — `https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n\n**Claim 6 — The system pairs the LLM with \"automated evaluators that verify answers.\"**\n> AlphaEvolve \"pairs the creative problem-solving capabilities of our Gemini models with automated evaluators that verify answers, and uses an evolutionary framework to improve upon the most promising ideas.\"\nSource: DeepMind blog post — same URL.\n\n---\n\n## B. Why this is a FUNDAMENTAL constraint (DeepMind's own caveats, verbatim)\n\n**Claim 7 — DeepMind explicitly frames the automated metric as both the advantage AND the limitation (this is the key caveat, stated up front in the paper).**\n> \"While the use of an automated evaluation metric offers AlphaEvolve a key advantage, it is also a limitation—in particular, it puts tasks that require manual experimentation out of our scope.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, intro / Table 1 region (line ~88) — `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf`\n\n**Claim 8 — The \"main limitation,\" verbatim from the paper's conclusion: it only handles problems for which an automated evaluator can be devised.**\n> \"The main limitation of AlphaEvolve is that it handles problems for which it is possible to devise an automated evaluator. While this is true of many problems in the mathematical and computational sciences, there are domains such as the natural sciences where only some experiments can be simulated or automated.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, Conclusion / Limitations (line ~1896) — same URL.\n\n**Claim 9 — Domain focus is a direct consequence of the constraint: math, CS, system optimization are chosen precisely because they permit automated metrics.**\n> \"Because problems in mathematics, computer science, and system optimization typically permit automated evaluation metrics, our efforts on AlphaEvolve focus on these domains.\"\nSource: White paper PDF (line ~90) — same URL.\n\n**Claim 10 — Blog post echoes the same scoping rationale.**\n> \"This makes AlphaEvolve particularly helpful in a broad range of domains where progress can be clearly and systematically measured, like in math and computer science.\"\nSource: DeepMind blog post — `https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n\n---\n\n## C. What classes of problems this EXCLUDES\n\n**Claim 11 — Tasks requiring manual experimentation are out of scope (verbatim, paper intro).** See Claim 7: \"...it puts tasks that require manual experimentation out of our scope.\"\nSource: White paper PDF (line ~89) — same URL.\n\n**Claim 12 — Natural sciences / wet-lab style work where experiments cannot be simulated or automated are excluded.** See Claim 8: \"...there are domains such as the natural sciences where only some experiments can be simulated or automated.\"\nSource: White paper PDF (line ~1898) — same URL.\n\n**Claim 13 — Non-numerical / non-algorithmic problems are a poor fit (secondary-source framing of the constraint).**\n> \"Because AlphaEvolve can only solve problems that it can self-evaluate, the system can only work with certain types of problems.\" and \"In another major limitation, AlphaEvolve can only describe solutions as algorithms, making it a poor fit for problems that aren't numerical.\" and \"They must also provide a mechanism for automatically assessing the system's answers in the form of a formula.\"\nSource: TechCrunch — `https://techcrunch.com/2025/05/14/deepmind-claims-its-newest-ai-tool-is-a-whiz-at-math-and-science-problems/`\n\n**Claim 14 — Subjective / qualitative outputs that cannot be captured in the programmatic score: DeepMind only partially addresses these, and explicitly has NOT optimized for it.**\n> \"While AlphaEvolve does allow for LLM-provided evaluation of ideas, this is not a setting we have optimized for.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, Conclusion (line ~1899) — `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf`\nThis is the important nuance: AlphaEvolve has an *optional* \"LLM-generated feedback\" mechanism for qualities \"difficult to capture precisely in the user-provided evaluation function ℎ\" (e.g. program simplicity) — but DeepMind states it is not a setting they optimized for, and the core loop still requires the machine score. (Optional LLM-feedback mechanism described in §2.4, same URL.)\n\n---\n\n## D. Supporting detail on the evaluator's machinery (reinforces that scoring is programmatic/automated)\n\n**Claim 15 — Evaluation can be a multi-stage automated cascade (hypothesis testing) and can run for ~100 compute-hours per candidate, parallelized.**\n> \"Evaluation cascade (hypothesis testing): the user can specify ensembles of test cases of increasing difficulty...\" and \"the sample efficiency of AlphaEvolve makes it feasible to spend on the order of 100 compute-hours to evaluate any new solution.\"\nSource: White paper PDF, §2.4 — same URL.\n\n**Claim 16 — Independent technical write-up confirms the per-iteration accept/reject is gated on the user-supplied evaluate function returning machine-gradable metrics.**\n> Every iteration \"is accepted or rejected based on a user-supplied 'evaluate' function that returns machine-gradable metrics.\"\nSource: VentureBeat — `https://venturebeat.com/ai/googles-alphaevolve-the-ai-agent-that-reclaimed-0-7-of-googles-compute-and-how-to-copy-it`\n\n---\n\n## Summary of the load-bearing point\n\nDeepMind itself states the constraint in two places almost identically: the evaluation metric is \"a key advantage\" but \"also a limitation,\" and the \"main limitation … is that it handles problems for which it is possible to devise an automated evaluator.\" The verifier (the `evaluate` function `h` returning a dict of scalars) is not an optional add-on — it is the selection signal for the entire evolutionary loop. Anything lacking a programmatic score (subjective/qualitative outputs, wet-lab/physical experimentation, non-numerical/non-algorithmic problems) is out of scope by construction; the only escape hatch DeepMind offers is optional LLM-as-judge feedback, which they explicitly note is \"not a setting we have optimized for.\"\n\n**The strongest verbatim DeepMind caveats to quote** are Claim 7 and Claim 8 (both from the white paper PDF), plus the \"machine-gradeable solutions … must provide a mechanism for automatically assessing\" line in Claim 1.\n\n(One caveat on secondary sources: I could not retrieve a working Ars Technica URL for this story; TechCrunch and VentureBeat are used instead and both directly corroborate the constraint framing.)"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":323,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1370,"cache_read_input_tokens":24611,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1370,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG29QJa12mvSa1KpLq7S","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"9dfb1fd9-32b5-4abf-afe6-77919435e980","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:43.355Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
